hould be—respected as equal partners in economic, social, and political life. Through participant observation, Taft explores how the movement has redefined relationships between kids and adults; how they put these ideas into practice within their organizations; and how they advocate for them in larger society. Ultimately, she encourages us to question the widely accepted beliefs that children should not work or participate in politics. The Kids Are in Charge is a provocative invitation to re-imagine childhood, power, and politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 0aChildren's rightszPeru. 0aSocial actionzPeru. 0aYouthxPolitical activityzPeru. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh  aInternational Labor Organization.  aLatin American childhoods.  aPaolo Freire.  aPeru.  aadultism.  aageism.  aally-ship.  aapprenticeship learning.  abecoming activist.  achild labor law.  achild labor.  achild workers.  achildhood studies.  achildren’s councils.  achildren’s organizations.  achildren’s participation.  achildren’s rights.  achildren’s work.  acoalitions.  acolonialism.  acritical pedagogy.  aeducational change.  aegalitarianism.  aethnography.  afamily violence.  aindigenous childhoods.  aintergenerational activism.  aintergenerational collaboration.  aintergenerational relationships.  amodalities of power.  apopular movements.  asocial movement outcomes.  asocial movements.  asocial theory.  atheories of childhood.  ayouth activism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071028108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311072272740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479870554423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479870